Examples Chap02

Chapter 2 examples and tidy examples for manipulating data/

Introduction

We will start in the Chapter 2 of the book: Regression methods in biostatistics: linear, logistic, survival, and repeated measures models, Vittinghoff et al.The first example to load a dataset is using the The western collaborative group study (WCGS). We will use tidyverse tools to load (read_csv) and visualize (ggplot).

Next we set the working directory to load data files, using setwd pointing to the working directory. And load the tidyverse package.

The first line of code loads the library for tidyverse, then sets the working directory to point at my user and the directory that I have copyed the data from Vittinghoffs book. Then shows 22 variables in lines (not all the observations) and the summary of the numerical variables, summary automatically estimates general statistics for the numerical variables of the dataset.

Including Plots

Lets see from the WCGS data a summery of the systolic blod pressure (sbp), followed by a histogram, were the theoretical best possible number of bins was estimated with the formula bins = 1 + 3.3log(3144) that results in about 13, so after using 15 bins, the binwith results in 9. Then there is a boxplot of the dbp variable and a scatter plot of the same varible, and finally ggplot is used to manipulate the point characteristics and finally we have the same ploit at figure 2.9 in the book.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    98.0   120.0   126.0   128.6   136.0   230.0

## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

Note that the echo = FALSE parameter was added to the code chunk to prevent printing of the R code that generated the plot.
